<heading box="[377,531,1682,1709]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="22" pageNumber="703" reason="2">
cf. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gilmore" authorityYear="1928" box="[410,531,1683,1709]" class="Reptilia" family="Cteniogenyidae" genus="Cteniogenys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="22" pageNumber="703" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[410,531,1683,1709]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">Cteniogenys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[385,522,1714,1740]" box="[385,522,1714,1740]" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">
(
<figureCitation box="[394,470,1714,1740]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="23.[132,143,1175,1192]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1133]" captionTargetId="figure-315@23.[132,1455,215,1133]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIG. 16. — Choristoder remains from Angeac-Charente: A-C, anterior dorsal vertebra of cf. Cteniogenys sp. (ANG M-20) in dorsal (A), ventral (B) and posterior (C) views; D, E, juvenile dorsal vertebral centrum (ANG M-47) in ventral (D) and oblique anterior (E) views. Scale bar: A-C, 1 mm; D, E, 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902073" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902073/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
A-E)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[130,777,1778,2028]" box="[132,277,1778,1804]" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[130,777,1778,2028]" lastBlockId="23.[130,775,1267,1358]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="704" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">
A characteristic robust vertebra (
<figureCitation box="[499,578,1810,1836]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="23.[132,143,1175,1192]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1133]" captionTargetId="figure-315@23.[132,1455,215,1133]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIG. 16. — Choristoder remains from Angeac-Charente: A-C, anterior dorsal vertebra of cf. Cteniogenys sp. (ANG M-20) in dorsal (A), ventral (B) and posterior (C) views; D, E, juvenile dorsal vertebral centrum (ANG M-47) in ventral (D) and oblique anterior (E) views. Scale bar: A-C, 1 mm; D, E, 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902073" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902073/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
A-C), as well as a smaller vertebra that probably belongs to a juvenile individual (
<figureCitation box="[141,266,1873,1900]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="23.[132,143,1175,1192]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1133]" captionTargetId="figure-315@23.[132,1455,215,1133]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIG. 16. — Choristoder remains from Angeac-Charente: A-C, anterior dorsal vertebra of cf. Cteniogenys sp. (ANG M-20) in dorsal (A), ventral (B) and posterior (C) views; D, E, juvenile dorsal vertebral centrum (ANG M-47) in ventral (D) and oblique anterior (E) views. Scale bar: A-C, 1 mm; D, E, 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902073" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902073/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">Fig. 16D, E</figureCitation>
), have been discovered among the microremains. Both centra are amphicoelous, with an opened neurocentral suture. Dorsally, a distinct longitudinal ridge is laterally bordered by longitudinal grooves on the floor of the neural canal (
<figureCitation box="[205,304,2001,2027]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="23.[132,143,1175,1192]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1133]" captionTargetId="figure-315@23.[132,1455,215,1133]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIG. 16. — Choristoder remains from Angeac-Charente: A-C, anterior dorsal vertebra of cf. Cteniogenys sp. (ANG M-20) in dorsal (A), ventral (B) and posterior (C) views; D, E, juvenile dorsal vertebral centrum (ANG M-47) in ventral (D) and oblique anterior (E) views. Scale bar: A-C, 1 mm; D, E, 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902073" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902073/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">Fig. 16A</figureCitation>
). In ventral view, the lower half of the cen- trum is pinched into a keel (
<figureCitation box="[1126,1226,1586,1613]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="23.[132,143,1175,1192]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1133]" captionTargetId="figure-315@23.[132,1455,215,1133]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIG. 16. — Choristoder remains from Angeac-Charente: A-C, anterior dorsal vertebra of cf. Cteniogenys sp. (ANG M-20) in dorsal (A), ventral (B) and posterior (C) views; D, E, juvenile dorsal vertebral centrum (ANG M-47) in ventral (D) and oblique anterior (E) views. Scale bar: A-C, 1 mm; D, E, 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902073" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902073/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">Fig. 16D</figureCitation>
). The margins of the cotyle are thick (
<figureCitation box="[995,1091,1618,1645]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="23.[132,143,1175,1192]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1133]" captionTargetId="figure-315@23.[132,1455,215,1133]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIG. 16. — Choristoder remains from Angeac-Charente: A-C, anterior dorsal vertebra of cf. Cteniogenys sp. (ANG M-20) in dorsal (A), ventral (B) and posterior (C) views; D, E, juvenile dorsal vertebral centrum (ANG M-47) in ventral (D) and oblique anterior (E) views. Scale bar: A-C, 1 mm; D, E, 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902073" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902073/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">Fig. 16E</figureCitation>
). All these characters are reminiscent of choristoderan reptiles (
<bibRefCitation author="EVANS S. E." box="[1146,1273,1650,1677]" pageId="22" pageNumber="703" pagination="187 - 99" refId="ref39234" refString="EVANS S. E. 1991. - The postcranial skeleton of the choristodere Cteniogenys (Reptilia: Diapsida) from the Middle Jurassic of England. Geobios 24 (2): 187 - 99. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0016 - 6995 (91) 80006 - L" type="journal article" year="1991">Evans 1991</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="AVERIANOV A. O. &amp; MARTIN T. &amp; EVANS S. E. &amp; BAKIROV A. A." pageId="22" pageNumber="703" pagination="46 - 50" refId="ref35876" refString="AVERIANOV A. O., MARTIN T., EVANS S. E. &amp; BAKIROV A. A. 2006. - First Jurassic Choristodera from Asia. Naturwissenschaften 93 (1): 46 - 50. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00114 - 005 - 0061 - 2" type="journal article" year="2006">
Averianov 
<emphasis box="[1403,1456,1650,1676]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
; Vullo 
<emphasis box="[955,1009,1682,1708]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">et al.</emphasis>
2014; 
<bibRefCitation author="HADDOUMI H. &amp; ALLAIN R. &amp; MESLOUH S. &amp; METAIS G. &amp; MONBARON M. &amp; PONS D. &amp; RAGE J. - C. &amp; VULLO R. &amp; ZOUHRI S. &amp; GHEERBRANT E." box="[1091,1343,1682,1708]" pageId="22" pageNumber="703" pagination="290 - 319" refId="ref40886" refString="HADDOUMI H., ALLAIN R., MESLOUH S., METAIS G., MONBARON M., PONS D., RAGE J. - C., VULLO R., ZOUHRI S. &amp; GHEERBRANT E. 2016. - Guelb el Ahmar (Bathonian, Anoual Syncline, eastern Morocco): first continental flora and fauna including mammals from the Middle Jurassic of Africa. Gondwana Research 29: 290 - 319. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. gr. 2014.12.004" type="journal article" year="2016">
Haddoumi 
<emphasis box="[1223,1277,1682,1708]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="LASSERON M. &amp; ALLAIN R. &amp; GHEERBRANT E. &amp; HADDOUMI H. &amp; JALIL N. - E. &amp; METAIS G. &amp; RAGE J. - C. &amp; VULLO R. &amp; ZOUHRI S." pageId="22" pageNumber="703" pagination="367 - 392" refId="ref42313" refString="LASSERON M., ALLAIN R., GHEERBRANT E., HADDOUMI H., JALIL N. - E., METAIS G., RAGE J. - C., VULLO R. &amp; ZOUHRI S. 2020. - New data on the microvertebrate fauna from the Upper Jurassic or lowest Cretaceous of Ksar Metlili (Anoual Syncline, eastern Morocco). Geological Magazine 157 (3): 367 - 392. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0016756819000761" type="journal article" year="2020">
Lasseron 
<emphasis box="[813,866,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
). ANG M-20 is nearly identical to the vertebra of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gilmore" authorityYear="1928" box="[843,964,1746,1772]" class="Reptilia" family="Cteniogenyidae" genus="Cteniogenys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="22" pageNumber="703" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[843,964,1746,1772]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">Cteniogenys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
figured by 
<bibRefCitation author="EVANS S. E. &amp; MILNER A. R." box="[1092,1341,1746,1772]" pageId="22" pageNumber="703" pagination="303 - 321" refId="ref39385" refString="EVANS S. E. &amp; MILNER A. R. 1994. - Microvertebrate faunas from the Middle Jurassic of Britain, in FRASER N. &amp; SUES H. - D. (eds), In the Shadow of the Dinosaurs: Early Mesozoic Tetrapods. CambridgeUniversity Press, Cambridge: 303 - 321." type="book chapter" year="1994">Evans &amp; Milner (1994</bibRefCitation>
: fig.18.5). Hence, it is here tentatively assigned to this genus, although this identification needs to be substantiated with additional material. These freshwater or amphibious diapsids are well known in Laurasia (
<bibRefCitation author="MATSUMOTO R. &amp; BUFFETAUT E. &amp; HERVET S. &amp; EVANS S. E." box="[1034,1286,1873,1900]" pageId="22" pageNumber="703" pagination="319 - 39" refId="ref43660" refString="MATSUMOTO R., BUFFETAUT E., ESCUILLIE F, HERVET S. &amp; EVANS S. E. 2013. - New material of the choristodere Lazarussuchus (Diapsida, Choristodera) from the Paleocene of France. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology 33 (2): 319 - 39. https: // doi. org / 10.10 80 / 02724634.2012.716274" type="journal article" year="2013">
Matsumoto 
<emphasis box="[1169,1222,1873,1899]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
), but have also been reported from the Jurassic-Cretaceous transition of North Africa (
<bibRefCitation author="LASSERON M. &amp; ALLAIN R. &amp; GHEERBRANT E. &amp; HADDOUMI H. &amp; JALIL N. - E. &amp; METAIS G. &amp; RAGE J. - C. &amp; VULLO R. &amp; ZOUHRI S." box="[890,1096,1937,1964]" pageId="22" pageNumber="703" pagination="367 - 392" refId="ref42313" refString="LASSERON M., ALLAIN R., GHEERBRANT E., HADDOUMI H., JALIL N. - E., METAIS G., RAGE J. - C., VULLO R. &amp; ZOUHRI S. 2020. - New data on the microvertebrate fauna from the Upper Jurassic or lowest Cretaceous of Ksar Metlili (Anoual Syncline, eastern Morocco). Geological Magazine 157 (3): 367 - 392. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0016756819000761" type="journal article" year="2020">
Lasseron 
<emphasis box="[987,1036,1937,1963]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="703">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
). In the Lower Cretaceous of Asia, the diversity and abundance of choristoderans is particularly high in the faunal assemblages, in which crocodyliforms are scarce (
<bibRefCitation author="MATSUMOTO R. &amp; MANABE M. &amp; EVANS S. E." box="[211,456,1267,1294]" pageId="23" pageNumber="704" pagination="583 - 594" refId="ref43772" refString="MATSUMOTO R., MANABE M. &amp; EVANS S. E. 2015. - The first record of a long-snouted choristodere (Reptilia, Diapsida) from the Early Cretaceous of Ishikawa Prefecture, Japan. Historical Biology 27: 583 - 594. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 08912963.2014.898296" type="journal article" year="2015">
Matsumoto 
<emphasis box="[343,394,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="704">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
; Skutschas &amp; Vitenko 2017). Conversely, the abundance and diversity of crocodyliforms at Angeac-Charente may explain the scaricity of choristoderans.
</paragraph>
